{
  "response": "# Interactive Bar/Line Chart Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.\n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA\n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver), keyboard-only users, low-vision users (zoom/reflow, contrast), users with color vision deficiencies, users with reduced-motion preferences.\n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA (Windows), JAWS (Windows), VoiceOver (macOS), keyboard-only navigation, browser zoom/reflow, OS high-contrast / forced-colors.\n\n**Feature:** An interactive SVG bar/line chart on a public analytics dashboard that compares 3\u20135 data series across 12 months, with a legend, axis labels, hover/focus tooltips, and interactive data points \u2014 currently inaccessible (no ARIA, hover-only tooltip, no keyboard nav, no screen-reader alternative).\n\n**Risk Level:** High (data visualization with custom SVG, custom interaction, dynamic tooltip content, and a 320px reflow constraint \u2014 multiple non-trivial WCAG surfaces interact).\n\n**Component Type:** Data visualization (SVG chart) + structured data table fallback + custom keyboard widget.\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\n**What is being built?** An accessibility layer for an existing custom-SVG chart component, so that the same data is available to screen-reader, keyboard-only, low-vision, and color-blind users without changing the visual chart.\n\n**What user need does it address?** Public-dashboard users need to *read and compare the underlying data* (3\u20135 series \u00d7 12 months), not merely know \"a chart exists.\" Sighted mouse users get this from bars/nodes + tooltips; everyone else currently gets nothing.\n\n**Who needs accessibility?**\n- Screen-reader users \u2014 need the actual numbers in a navigable structure, not a visual description.\n- Keyboard-only users \u2014 need to reach the chart, move between data points, and trigger the tooltip equivalent without a mouse.\n- Low-vision users \u2014 need 200% zoom and 320px reflow to work, plus sufficient contrast on text, axes, and focus rings.\n- Color-blind users \u2014 must distinguish 3\u20135 series without relying on hue alone (deuteranopia/protanopia/tritanopia).\n- Reduced-motion users \u2014 chart animation must not be forced on them.\n\n**Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA.\n\n**Assistive technologies to support:** NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver, keyboard-only, browser zoom/reflow, forced-colors mode.\n\n**Risk level:** High. Drivers: custom SVG (inconsistent AT semantics across NVDA/JAWS/VoiceOver), dynamic tooltip content on hover/focus (1.4.13), color-coded legend (1.4.1), and a hard 320px reflow requirement (1.4.10) for a fundamentally wide visual.\n\n**What existing code does this modify/extend?** The existing `Chart` React component (custom SVG renderer). Current state per the brief: the SVG root has **no ARIA attributes**, the tooltip is **hover-only**, and there is **no keyboard navigation and no screen-reader alternative**. This plan adds an accessibility layer around the existing renderer; it does not rewrite the renderer and does not touch the data pipeline that supplies the series. *(Implementation note: cite the actual `Chart.tsx:line` for the SVG root and the tooltip handler when editing \u2014 the fixture supplies prose, not line numbers.)*\n\n**Constraints (from the brief):**\n- Custom SVG renderer must remain \u2014 **no** migration to recharts/victory.\n- Visual chart (colors, tooltips, animation) must remain unchanged \u2014 accessibility is **additive**, not a redesign.\n- A data-table fallback **is acceptable as an addition**.\n- The chart is sometimes embedded in a responsive container that narrows to **320px** on mobile.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Decision (the central choice for this AMBIGUOUS fixture)\n\nThere is no single correct way to make a chart accessible. I evaluated three candidate strategies and **commit to a layered approach**; the layers are coherent because each serves a distinct user category and they share one source of truth (the series data already in the component).\n\n| Candidate | What it is | Why NOT as the *primary* data path |\n|---|---|---|\n| **A. `role=\"img\"` + `aria-label` only** | One SVG, one summary label describing the chart | A summary alone cannot convey 36\u201360 individual values. Screen-reader users could hear \"Line chart comparing 5 series over 12 months\" but never reach a single number. Fails the *data access* intent of 1.1.1 for an informative graphic. Good as a **wrapper label**, insufficient alone. |\n| **B. Full SVG ARIA grid / `role=\"graphics-document\"` with per-node roles** | Mark every bar/node with `role`, `aria-label`, build a roving-tabindex grid inside the SVG | Brittle: SVG ARIA support is uneven across NVDA/JAWS/VoiceOver; `<g>`/`<rect>` + ARIA roles are inconsistently exposed; high implementation/maintenance cost; easy to ship something that *looks* annotated but reads as garbage. The fixture explicitly warns against \"over-specifying complex SVG ARIA patterns without considering the simpler, more robust data table alternative.\" |\n| **C. HTML data table fallback** | A real `<table>` carrying every value, linked to the chart | Robust, universally supported semantics (row/column headers, navigable cell-by-cell), trivially correct in all three screen readers. The natural primary data path. Needs a deliberate plan for *where it renders* and *how it is styled* for SR vs. sighted users. |\n\n**Chosen architecture \u2014 layered, table-as-source-of-truth:**\n\n1. **Wrapper:** A labeled `role=\"figure\"` region wrapping the SVG + the table, with a `<figcaption>`-style accessible name and a one-sentence `role=\"img\"` summary on the SVG itself (strategy A as a *label*, not as the data path).\n2. **Primary screen-reader data path:** A real, always-present-in-DOM **HTML `<table>`** containing every value (strategy C). It is **visually hidden by default** (so the visual design is unchanged per the constraint) but **toggleable to visible** via a \"Show data table\" button \u2014 which simultaneously satisfies the 320px reflow path and gives *sighted keyboard users and low-vision users* a non-SVG way to read exact values.\n3. **Keyboard + focus tooltip layer:** Data points (bars/nodes) are made keyboard-navigable with a **roving tabindex** and **Arrow-key** movement, and the existing tooltip is upgraded to appear on **focus** as well as hover (strategy B's interaction value, *without* relying on SVG ARIA to carry the data). This is an *enhancement* on top of the table, not the sole path \u2014 so if a given screen reader exposes the SVG poorly, the table still carries 100% of the data.\n\n**Why this tradeoff:** The table guarantees correctness and full data access everywhere (de-risks the SVG-AT inconsistency); `role=\"img\"` + summary gives a fast orientation without forcing users to read 60 cells to learn what the chart *is*; the keyboard/focus tooltip layer makes the *visual* chart itself operable and fixes the 1.4.13 hover-only failure for sighted keyboard users. One data source feeds all three, so they cannot drift.\n\n**Negative space \u2014 what this plan does NOT claim:** It does not claim the SVG nodes will be a fully spec-conforming ARIA grid in every screen reader; the table is the guaranteed path and the SVG keyboard layer is a progressive enhancement. It does not cover the data pipeline (out of scope). It does not change chart colors, tooltip visuals, or animation (constraint).\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\n**Landmark / region context:** The chart lives inside the dashboard's existing `<main>`. The component contributes a single labeled region; it does **not** introduce a new top-level landmark.\n\n**Heading hierarchy:** The chart has a visible title (e.g., \"Monthly Active Users by Plan\"). That title is the chart's accessible name. If the surrounding page uses headings, the title should be a heading at the correct level (e.g., `<h2>`/`<h3>`) so it appears in the screen-reader heading list and establishes the chart in the document outline \u2014 no level skips (WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; 2.4.6 Headings and Labels).\n\n**Region semantics:** Wrap the chart + table + controls in a `role=\"figure\"` (or `<figure>`) with an accessible name from the title, so screen-reader users can jump to it and so the table is announced as belonging to the figure (WCAG 1.3.1).\n\n**Table structure:** The fallback table is a real `<table>` with:\n- A `<caption>` naming it (e.g., \"Monthly Active Users by Plan \u2014 data table\").\n- A header row: first column header \"Month\" (`<th scope=\"col\">`), then one `<th scope=\"col\">` per series (the series name \u2014 same text as the legend label).\n- One `<tr>` per month (12 rows); the month cell is `<th scope=\"row\">` and each value cell is `<td>`. **Loop-generated identifying cells (the month) must be `<th scope=\"row\">`, never `<td>`** so each value is announced with its month and series (WCAG 1.3.1). Do **not** apply `role=\"presentation\"` to this table \u2014 it is a data table and must keep its semantics.\n\n**Skip link:** Not required for a single component; the page-level skip-to-main link already covers it (WCAG 2.4.1). No new bypass mechanism needed here.\n\n**HTML structure stub (structure only \u2014 not implementation code):**\n\n```\n<figure  role=\"figure\"  aria-labelledby=\"chart-title-id\">\n  <figcaption id=\"chart-title-id\">  \u2190 visible chart title (also the heading)\n    Monthly Active Users by Plan\n  </figcaption>\n\n  <!-- Controls row -->\n  <button aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"chart-table-id\">\n    Show data table\n  </button>\n  <!-- (existing bar/line toggle prop control, if user-facing, labeled here) -->\n\n  <!-- The visual chart, unchanged visually -->\n  <svg role=\"img\" aria-labelledby=\"chart-title-id\" aria-describedby=\"chart-summary-id\">\n     \u2026 existing bars/nodes/axes/legend, now keyboard-navigable \u2026\n  </svg>\n  <p id=\"chart-summary-id\" class=\"sr-only\">  \u2190 data-oriented summary sentence\n    Line chart comparing 5 plans across 12 months (Jan\u2013Dec). Highest: Enterprise,\n    peaking at 4,210 in November. Lowest: Free, ranging 180\u2013540. Full values in the data table.\n  </p>\n\n  <!-- Status region for tooltip/announcements -->\n  <div class=\"sr-only\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\"></div>\n\n  <!-- Primary data path: real table, sr-only until toggled -->\n  <table id=\"chart-table-id\" class=\"sr-only\">  \u2190 class swapped to visible when toggled\n    <caption>Monthly Active Users by Plan \u2014 data table</caption>\n    <thead>\n      <tr>\n        <th scope=\"col\">Month</th>\n        <th scope=\"col\">Free</th> \u2026 <th scope=\"col\">Enterprise</th>\n      </tr>\n    </thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr><th scope=\"row\">January</th><td>180</td> \u2026 <td>3,120</td></tr>\n      \u202612 rows\u2026\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n</figure>\n```\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\nThe chart is **not** a standard APG widget; it is a custom graphics widget. I map each interactive piece to the closest APG pattern and reuse its keyboard contract so behavior is predictable.\n\n- **Chart data-point navigation** \u2192 modeled on the APG **Grid** pattern for 2-D arrow-key movement (rows = series, columns = months), with a **roving tabindex** so the chart is a single Tab stop. APG Grid: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/ . (We borrow the *keyboard model*, not necessarily `role=\"grid\"` on the SVG \u2014 see State section; the table provides the guaranteed grid semantics.)\n- **\"Show data table\" toggle** \u2192 APG **Disclosure** pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/ . Button with `aria-expanded` and `aria-controls`.\n- **Focus/hover tooltip** \u2192 APG **Tooltip** pattern for the *content-on-focus* contract (appears on focus, dismissible with Escape, does not steal focus, hoverable): https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/tooltip/ . This directly addresses WCAG 1.4.13.\n- **Bar/line type toggle** (the existing prop, if surfaced as a user control) \u2192 native `<button>` or a labeled control; if it is a developer-only prop and not user-facing, no widget is needed (document which it is during implementation).\n\n**Keyboard interaction model (data points):**\n\n| Key | Action |\n|---|---|\n| Tab | Move focus *to* the chart (lands on the last-focused data point, default the first point of the first series). One Tab stop for the whole chart (roving tabindex). |\n| Right / Left Arrow | Move to next/previous **month** within the current series; tooltip updates to the newly focused point. |\n| Up / Down Arrow | Move to the same month in the **previous/next series**. |\n| Home / End | First / last month of the current series. |\n| Enter / Space | Toggle a \"pinned\" tooltip for the focused point (so it persists while the user reads it); pressing again unpins. (Tooltip already appears on focus; this lets the user lock it.) |\n| Escape | Dismiss/unpin the tooltip without moving focus (WCAG 1.4.13 *dismissible*). |\n| Tab (again) | Move focus *out* of the chart to the next interactive element (does not cycle within). |\n\n**Screen-reader experience:**\n- On entering the figure: name \"Monthly Active Users by Plan, figure,\" then the summary sentence (via `aria-describedby` on the SVG) gives orientation.\n- The **data table** is where values are read: navigating cells announces \"January, Enterprise, 3,120\" because of `scope` headers.\n- On a focused data point (keyboard layer): the point exposes an accessible name like \"Enterprise, November: 4,210\" (via `aria-label` on the focusable node) and the polite `role=\"status\"` region echoes the same string so AT that under-exposes SVG still hears the value.\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard | ARIA | WCAG |\n|--------|-------------|----------|------|------|\n| Data points (bars/nodes) | Grid (2-D arrow nav) | Tab in/out; Arrows move; Home/End; Enter/Space pin; Esc dismiss | Roving `tabindex` (0/-1); focusable node `aria-label=\"{series}, {month}: {value}\"`; live echo in `role=\"status\"` | 2.1.1 Keyboard; 2.4.3 Focus Order; 2.4.7 Focus Visible; 4.1.2 Name/Role/Value; 1.4.13 |\n| \"Show data table\" toggle | Disclosure | Tab; Enter/Space toggles | `<button>` `aria-expanded` (true/false), `aria-controls=\"chart-table-id\"` | 4.1.2; 1.3.1 |\n| Focus/hover tooltip | Tooltip | Appears on focus; Esc dismisses; pin via Enter/Space | Tooltip element `role=\"tooltip\"` id referenced by focused point's `aria-describedby`; never steals focus | 1.4.13; 4.1.2 |\n| Bar/line type control (if user-facing) | Button (or toggle button) | Tab; Enter/Space | `<button>`; if stateful, `aria-pressed` | 4.1.2; 1.4.1 (state not color-only) |\n| Data table | (native semantics) | Standard table reading keys | Real `<table>`, `scope` headers, `<caption>` | 1.3.1; 1.1.1 |\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n**Tab order (document order, matches visual top-to-bottom):**\n1. Chart title heading (not focusable; appears in heading list).\n2. \"Show data table\" toggle button.\n3. (Bar/line type control, if user-facing.)\n4. The chart (single Tab stop via roving tabindex \u2192 focused data point).\n5. If the table is toggled visible, it follows in DOM order; its cells are read with normal table-reading keys, not Tab stops.\n\nThis order matches the visual reading order (controls above chart, table below), satisfying WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order and 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n\n**Roving tabindex (composite widget):** Exactly one data point has `tabindex=\"0\"`; all others `tabindex=\"-1\"`. Arrow keys move the `0` to the newly focused point and call `.focus()` on it. This keeps the chart a single Tab stop and is the APG-prescribed composite-widget technique (WCAG 2.1.1; 2.4.3).\n\n**Focus visibility:** The focused bar/node must show a **visible focus ring that does not depend on the chart colors**. Use a **two-color (double-ring) indicator** \u2014 e.g., a dark outline plus a light halo (or an SVG focus rectangle with both a light and dark stroke) \u2014 so it is visible against any series color and against both light and dark chart backgrounds. Minimum 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors (WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible; 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast). Use `:focus-visible` semantics so the ring shows for keyboard users without flashing on mouse click. Do **not** rely solely on the tooltip appearing as the \"focus indicator\" \u2014 the focused element itself must be visibly indicated.\n\n**No focus trap needed:** The chart is inline content, not a modal. Tab must be able to leave the chart in both directions. The only \"trap-like\" behavior is roving tabindex *within* the chart while it has focus, which is correct composite-widget behavior, not a keyboard trap (WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap \u2014 verify Tab exits cleanly).\n\n**Focus restoration:**\n- Toggling the data table open/closed must **not** move focus away from the toggle button; focus stays on the button (whose `aria-expanded` flips). The newly revealed table is in the tab/reading order after it, reachable by continuing to navigate \u2014 no focus jump.\n- Dismissing the tooltip with Escape must **leave focus on the current data point** (do not move focus). Re-focusing or arrowing re-shows it.\n\n**Tooltip and focus:** The tooltip must **never receive or steal focus** (APG Tooltip). It is associated to the focused point via `aria-describedby` and/or echoed through the `role=\"status\"` region; focus remains on the data point.\n\n**Hidden-content strategy (critical detail):** The visually-hidden table and `sr-only` summary must remain **in the accessibility tree** (use the `.sr-only` clip technique: 1px clip, not `display:none`, not `visibility:hidden`, not `aria-hidden`). Conversely, any *decorative* SVG sub-parts that are NOT data (gridlines, the chart's own internal hover layer) should be hidden from AT with `aria-hidden=\"true\"` so they don't add noise. Remember `aria-hidden` alone does not remove focusability \u2014 decorative SVG elements must also not be in the tab order (don't give them `tabindex`).\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\nEvery state below is communicated **both visually and programmatically**; color is never the sole signal (WCAG 1.4.1).\n\n**States to communicate:**\n- Data table hidden vs. shown (disclosure expanded/collapsed).\n- Data point focused vs. not focused.\n- Tooltip visible vs. hidden vs. pinned.\n- Chart type = bar vs. line (if user-switchable).\n- Series identity (legend) \u2014 *which color is which series* (the core 1.4.1 problem).\n- Loading vs. loaded (if the chart can re-fetch; per scope the data pipeline is out of scope, but the *rendering* busy state is in scope if a re-render is observable).\n\n**Live regions:**\n- One **polite** `role=\"status\"` (`aria-live=\"polite\"`) region inside the figure, used to echo the focused point's \"{series}, {month}: {value}\" as the user arrows around, and to announce \"Data table shown / hidden.\" Polite, because none of this is an error or urgent interruption (WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages).\n- **No** `aria-live=\"assertive\"` / `role=\"alert\"` anywhere here \u2014 there are no urgent errors in a read-only chart. **There must be exactly ONE status region for the whole chart**, not one per data point; never place a live region inside the per-point render loop (that would create dozens of competing regions).\n- If a `busy` state is observable during re-render, set `aria-busy=\"true\"` on the figure while rendering and `false` when done (WCAG 4.1.3).\n\n**Legend / series identity \u2014 the 1.4.1 centerpiece:** Three reinforcing, non-color signals so 3\u20135 series are distinguishable without hue:\n1. **Direct text label** on/next to each legend swatch (the series name) \u2014 already textual, but ensure the name, not just the color, is the legend's accessible content.\n2. **Pattern / shape differentiation in the chart marks** so the *plotted data itself* is distinguishable without color:\n   - **Bar mode:** apply distinct **SVG pattern fills** per series (e.g., solid, diagonal hatch, dots, cross-hatch, vertical lines) in addition to color.\n   - **Line mode:** apply distinct **line dash patterns** (solid, dashed, dotted, dash-dot) **and** distinct **point marker shapes** (circle, square, triangle, diamond) per series.\n3. The **legend swatch** repeats the same pattern/shape it uses in the chart, so the mapping is learnable without color.\n\nThis means a user with full color blindness (or in forced-colors mode) can still tell the series apart by texture/shape/label. *(Constraint check: this adds pattern/shape **in addition to** the existing colors \u2014 it does not change the existing colors, so the \"visual chart unchanged\" constraint is respected as an additive enhancement; confirm with design that additive patterns are acceptable. If design refuses pattern fills, the **data table** still fully disambiguates series, so 1.4.1 is satisfied via the table even in the worst case.)*\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual | Programmatic | ARIA | WCAG |\n|-------|--------|-------------|------|------|\n| Table hidden / shown | Button label + table absent/visible | Disclosure state | `aria-expanded` on button; `role=\"status\"` says \"Data table shown/hidden\" | 4.1.2; 4.1.3; 1.3.1 |\n| Data point focused | Double-ring focus indicator on bar/node | Focus moves to node; name exposed | `tabindex` roving; `aria-label=\"{series},{month}:{value}\"` | 2.4.7; 4.1.2 |\n| Tooltip visible / pinned / hidden | Tooltip box shown; pinned style if locked | Described-by association; live echo | `role=\"tooltip\"`; point `aria-describedby`; Esc dismiss | 1.4.13; 4.1.2 |\n| Chart type bar/line | Different render + control state | Toggle pressed state | `aria-pressed` (if toggle) \u2014 never color-only | 4.1.2; 1.4.1 |\n| Series identity | Color **+ pattern/shape + text label** | Series name in legend, table headers, point labels | (text/markup, not ARIA) | **1.4.1**; 1.1.1 |\n| Rendering busy (if observable) | (spinner/disabled, if any) | Busy flagged | `aria-busy` on figure | 4.1.3 |\n\n**Symbol note:** If any legend or control uses bare glyphs (e.g., a \"\u25be\" on the disclosure, \"\u00d7\" to dismiss), wrap the glyph in `<span aria-hidden=\"true\">` and give the control a real text/`aria-label` name, so screen readers don't announce \"down-pointing triangle\" / \"times\" redundantly (WCAG 4.1.2).\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n**Color contrast (WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum; 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast):**\n- Axis labels, tick labels, legend text, tooltip text: \u2265 **4.5:1** against their background (normal text). Title may qualify as large text (\u2265 3:1) if \u2265 18px / 14px bold \u2014 document which.\n- Axis lines, gridlines, chart borders, focus ring, and the series marks themselves (as UI/graphical objects that convey meaning) must meet **3:1** non-text contrast against adjacent colors. *Verify each of the 3\u20135 series colors against the chart background and against each other where they overlap.*\n- **Do not change the existing series colors** (constraint) \u2014 but **measure** them. If any existing series color fails 3:1 against the background or is indistinguishable from a neighbor for color-blind users, the pattern/shape differentiation (above) and the data table are the compliant fallbacks; flag the failing color to design as a follow-up.\n\n**Color is never the only signal (WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color):** Covered above \u2014 every series carries pattern/shape + text label; the table fully disambiguates. The legend's meaning survives grayscale and forced-colors. Test by viewing the chart in grayscale and in OS high-contrast.\n\n**Forced-colors / high-contrast mode (WCAG 1.4.11):** In forced-colors mode, SVG fills may be overridden. Ensure the focus ring, axis lines, and at least the *shape/dash* differentiation survive (pattern/marker shapes are more robust than fills here). The data table inherits forced-colors text styling automatically and remains fully readable \u2014 another reason the table is the safety net.\n\n**Font sizing / zoom (WCAG 1.4.4 Resize Text; 1.4.10 Reflow):** Use relative units (`rem`/`em`) for all chart text so 200% zoom enlarges labels. The chart container must reflow (see below).\n\n**Reflow at 320px \u2014 WCAG 1.4.10 (the hard constraint):** A 12-month, 5-series chart cannot shrink to 320px and stay legible, and **horizontal scrolling of the whole page is not allowed**. Plan, in priority order:\n1. **Primary strategy \u2014 swap to the data table at narrow widths.** At \u2264 ~480px (covering the 320px case), **render the data table as the default visible representation** and collapse the SVG (or make the SVG horizontally scrollable *within its own container only* with the table available). The table reflows naturally to 320px (it's just text in rows), giving narrow-viewport users full data with **no page-level horizontal scroll**. This reuses the same table that screen-reader users get \u2014 one artifact, two jobs.\n2. If product wants the visual chart on mobile too, the SVG may live in a **container with its own `overflow-x:auto`** (an exception-permitted scrolling region for the 2-D data graphic), but the data table must still be present so scrolling is never the *only* way to get the data.\n3. Sticky headers/controls must not consume the narrow viewport \u2014 keep the \"Show data table\" control compact at 320px.\n\nNet: **at 320px, the data table is shown and there is no horizontal page scroll** \u2014 1.4.10 satisfied.\n\n**Animation / motion (WCAG 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions; 2.2.2 if anything auto-updates):** The existing entrance/transition animation must respect `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` \u2014 disable or reduce chart animations for those users. (The constraint says \"animation must remain unchanged\" *visually*, but reduced-motion gating is an accessibility requirement; gate the animation behind the media query rather than removing it for everyone.) No essential information may be conveyed *only* through motion.\n\n**Touch target sizing (WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum)):** The \"Show data table\" button, the bar/line toggle, and any dismiss control must be **\u2265 24\u00d724 CSS px** (2.2 AA minimum) \u2014 target \u2265 44\u00d744 for comfort. Individual data points (bars/nodes) are exempt as inline data-graphic essentials, but the table gives an alternative way to read each value, so small bars don't block access.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n**The SVG root `aria-label` / summary \u2014 exactly what it says (per the fixture's explicit ask):**\n- The SVG carries `role=\"img\"`, `aria-labelledby` \u2192 the visible title, and `aria-describedby` \u2192 a **data-oriented** summary sentence (NOT a visual description).\n- **Good summary (data-oriented):** *\"Line chart comparing 5 plans (Free, Starter, Pro, Business, Enterprise) across 12 months. Enterprise is highest, peaking at 4,210 in November; Free is lowest, 180\u2013540. Full values available in the data table below.\"*\n- **Bad summary (visual-only \u2014 explicitly disallowed by the fixture):** ~~\"A line chart with blue, red, green, orange, and purple lines.\"~~ Color/appearance description is not data access.\n- The summary names the series, the overall trend/extremes, and **points to the data table** for exact values (WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content).\n\n**Screen-reader data access path (committed, single strategy):** A real **HTML `<table class=\"sr-only\">`** in the DOM (the layered architecture's primary path). It is:\n- **Where it renders:** inside the figure, after the SVG, in document order.\n- **How it's linked:** it is part of the same labeled figure; the SVG summary explicitly references \"the data table below,\" and the disclosure button's `aria-controls` points to it.\n- **How it's styled for SR vs. sighted:** `.sr-only` (1px clip-rect, not `display:none`) keeps it in the accessibility tree for screen readers while invisible to sighted users; the \"Show data table\" toggle swaps the class to render it visibly for sighted keyboard / low-vision users and for the 320px reflow case. One table, both audiences (WCAG 1.1.1; 1.3.1).\n\n**Alt text on embedded glyph/marker images:** The SVG markers/patterns are drawn, not `<img>`, so no `alt` per-mark. If any legend swatch is an `<img>`, it should be `alt=\"\"` (decorative) because the adjacent text label carries the meaning \u2014 avoid double-announcing (WCAG 1.1.1). If a marker is the *sole* accessible name of a focusable point, that name lives in the point's `aria-label`, and any decorative inner SVG gets `aria-hidden`.\n\n**Link/control text quality (WCAG 2.4.4; 2.5.3 Label in Name):** \"Show data table\" / \"Hide data table\" is descriptive; the visible text matches the accessible name. No \"click here.\"\n\n**Form labels:** No form inputs in this component. The toggle button(s) have visible text labels (no label-less icon buttons); if an icon-only control is unavoidable, it gets an `aria-label` (never `title` as the accessible name) \u2014 and a visible text label is preferred (WCAG 1.3.1; 4.1.2).\n\n**Language:** Inherits `<html lang>`; series names that are non-English get `lang` on their cell/legend text if applicable (WCAG 3.1.1/3.1.2). Likely N/A.\n\n**Reading order (WCAG 1.3.2):** DOM order = title \u2192 controls \u2192 SVG \u2192 summary \u2192 table = visual order. No CSS reordering that diverges from DOM.\n\n**Number formatting:** Values in the table and tooltips are formatted with thousands separators and units (e.g., \"4,210 users\") so they're spoken intelligibly; avoid raw unformatted floats.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n**1. Automated (axe-core via a11y-test / `npx playwright test`):**\n- Run axe-core on **every state variant**: table hidden, table shown, bar mode, line mode, tooltip open, and at 320px / 200% zoom.\n- axe **will** catch: missing/empty accessible name on the SVG and buttons, color-contrast on text, table header/`scope` problems, `aria-*` misuse, heading order.\n- axe **will NOT** catch: whether the summary is data-oriented vs. visual, whether Arrow-key navigation works, whether the tooltip appears on focus, whether the live region actually announces, whether series are distinguishable without color, whether 320px avoids horizontal scroll meaningfully. Those need manual + AT testing.\n\n**2. Manual keyboard testing (a11y-test, real key events via Playwright `page.keyboard.press` / agent-browser CDP \u2014 not synthetic events):**\n- Tab reaches the toggle, then the chart as a **single** stop; Tab exits the chart cleanly both directions (no trap \u2014 WCAG 2.1.2).\n- Arrow keys move between data points (Left/Right = months, Up/Down = series); Home/End jump within a series.\n- Tooltip **appears on focus** of a data point (1.4.13), Escape dismisses it without moving focus, Enter/Space pins/unpins.\n- Disclosure: Enter/Space toggles the table; focus stays on the button; `aria-expanded` flips.\n- Focus ring is **visible on every data point** against every series color and on both light/dark backgrounds, at 100% and 200% zoom (2.4.7).\n\n**3. Screen-reader testing (real AT \u2014 NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver):**\n- Figure is announced with its name; the summary sentence is heard and is about *data*, not colors.\n- The **data table** reads each value with month + series headers (\"January, Enterprise, 3,120\") in all three SRs \u2014 this is the must-pass path.\n- Focused data points announce \"{series}, {month}: {value}\"; the `role=\"status\"` echo is heard as the user arrows (confirm it does not double-speak annoyingly \u2014 tune politeness).\n- Confirm decorative gridlines/hover layers are silent (`aria-hidden` working).\n- Cross-SR check: if SVG node labels are weak in one SR, verify the **table still delivers 100% of the data** there.\n\n**4. Visual / reflow / color regression:**\n- **320px:** load in a 320px CSS-width container \u2192 the data table is shown and **there is no horizontal page scroll** (1.4.10). Capture screenshot.\n- **200% zoom:** labels enlarge, layout reflows, no clipped text (1.4.4/1.4.10).\n- **Grayscale + forced-colors:** series remain distinguishable via pattern/shape/label; focus ring and axes survive (1.4.1/1.4.11). Capture screenshots.\n- **prefers-reduced-motion:** animation is disabled/reduced (2.3.3).\n\n**5. DOM verification (mandatory \u2014 not optional):** Inspect the **rendered** DOM (not just the source) to confirm: the SVG root actually has `role=\"img\"` + `aria-labelledby` + `aria-describedby` and the referenced ids **resolve to real elements**; the table is present with `<th scope=\"col\">`/`<th scope=\"row\">` on the right cells; `aria-controls` on the toggle resolves to the table id; the roving `tabindex` has exactly one `0`; the live region exists exactly **once**. Automated + visual inspection alone are insufficient \u2014 confirm attributes land on the correct elements and references resolve.\n\n**Acceptance criteria (per surface):**\n- A screen-reader user can obtain **every one** of the 36\u201360 values via the data table (pass/fail binary). \u2714\n- Keyboard user can navigate all data points and trigger each tooltip on focus; Escape dismisses; Tab exits. \u2714\n- At 320px, full data is available with **no horizontal page scroll**. \u2714\n- Series are distinguishable in grayscale/forced-colors without relying on hue. \u2714\n- axe-core: **0** serious/critical violations in every state variant. \u2714\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Labeled figure wrapper + data-oriented SVG summary\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 1**\n\n**Files:** `Chart.tsx` (SVG root + wrapper), `Chart.module.css` (sr-only utility), `Chart.test.tsx`.\n**Structure Stub:** `figure[role=figure][aria-labelledby=title]` > visible `figcaption` title (as heading) + `svg[role=img][aria-labelledby=title][aria-describedby=summary]` + `p#summary.sr-only` (data-oriented sentence).\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"img\"` on SVG \u2014 WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content; 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n- `aria-labelledby` \u2192 title id \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1; 2.4.6.\n- `aria-describedby` \u2192 summary id \u2014 WCAG 1.1.1.\n- Summary text describes **data** (series, extremes, trend), not appearance.\n**Keyboard:** None new (title not focusable).\n**Tests:** SVG has resolvable label + description; summary mentions series names + extremes, not colors; heading appears in heading list.\n**WCAG:** 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 2.4.6, 4.1.2.\n\n### Task 2: Visually-hidden data table (primary SR data path)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 2**\n\n**Files:** `ChartDataTable.tsx`, `Chart.module.css`, `ChartDataTable.test.tsx`.\n**Structure Stub:** `table#chart-table.sr-only` > `caption` + `thead`(`th[scope=col]` Month + per-series) + `tbody`(12\u00d7 `tr` with `th[scope=row]` month + `td` values).\n**ARIA / semantics:** Real `<table>`; `scope=\"col\"`/`scope=\"row\"`; `<caption>`. **No `role=\"presentation\"`.** Month cell is `<th scope=\"row\">` (loop-generated identifying cell). \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1; 1.1.1.\n**Keyboard:** Standard table-reading keys (AT-provided); not Tab stops.\n**Tests (incl. DOM verification):** 12 data rows \u00d7 N series; every month is `th[scope=row]`; every series header is `th[scope=col]`; values match the chart's data source exactly; table present in DOM even when visually hidden.\n**WCAG:** 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.4.10 (reflow path).\n\n### Task 3: \"Show data table\" disclosure + 320px reflow swap\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 3**\n\n**Files:** `Chart.tsx`, `Chart.module.css`, `Chart.test.tsx`.\n**Structure Stub:** `button[aria-expanded][aria-controls=chart-table]` \"Show/Hide data table\"; CSS media query (\u2264480px) renders the table visible by default and collapses/scopes the SVG.\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `aria-expanded` (true/false) \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls` \u2192 table id \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1.\n- `role=\"status\"` announces \"Data table shown/hidden\" \u2014 WCAG 4.1.3.\n**Keyboard:** Tab to button; Enter/Space toggles; focus **stays on button** after toggle.\n**Tests (incl. reflow):** Toggle flips `aria-expanded` and table visibility; focus unmoved; at 320px container the table is visible and **no horizontal page scroll**; `aria-controls` resolves.\n**WCAG:** 1.3.1, 1.4.10, 4.1.2, 4.1.3.\n\n### Task 4: Keyboard navigation of data points (roving tabindex, Grid model)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 4**\n\n**Files:** `Chart.tsx` (focusable nodes + key handler), `Chart.module.css` (focus ring), `ChartKeyboard.test.tsx`.\n**Structure Stub:** Each bar/node focusable, roving `tabindex` (one `0`, rest `-1`), `aria-label=\"{series}, {month}: {value}\"`; key handler implements Arrows/Home/End/Enter/Space/Esc; one `role=\"status\"` echo region (outside the per-point loop).\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- Roving `tabindex` 0/-1 \u2014 WCAG 2.1.1; 2.4.3.\n- `aria-label` per focusable point \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Single `role=\"status\"` live echo \u2014 WCAG 4.1.3.\n**Keyboard:** Per the keyboard table (Arrows move; Home/End; Enter/Space pin; Esc dismiss; Tab in/out, no trap).\n**Tests (real key events):** Arrow movement maps correctly (months/series); exactly one `tabindex=0` at a time; Tab exits both directions; live region echoes focused value; only one live region exists in DOM.\n**WCAG:** 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 4.1.2, 4.1.3.\n\n### Task 5: Focus-triggered tooltip (fix 1.4.13)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 5**\n\n**Files:** `Tooltip.tsx` (or existing tooltip upgraded), `Chart.tsx`, `Tooltip.test.tsx`.\n**Structure Stub:** `div[role=tooltip]#tip` referenced by the focused point's `aria-describedby`; shows on **focus** and on hover; Escape dismisses; hoverable; does **not** receive focus.\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"tooltip\"` + focused point `aria-describedby` \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Appears on focus (not hover-only); dismissible (Esc); persistent/hoverable \u2014 WCAG **1.4.13 Content on Hover or Focus**.\n**Keyboard:** Tooltip appears when a data point receives focus; Esc dismisses without moving focus; Enter/Space pins.\n**Tests:** Focusing a point shows the tooltip (keyboard, no mouse); content matches the point's value; Esc hides it; tooltip never steals focus; tooltip content is hoverable without dismissing.\n**WCAG:** 1.4.13, 4.1.2.\n\n### Task 6: Color-independent series differentiation (legend + marks)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 6**\n\n**Files:** `Chart.tsx` (SVG `<pattern>`/dash/marker defs), `Legend.tsx`, contrast audit notes.\n**Structure Stub:** Per-series SVG pattern fill (bar) / dash + marker shape (line); legend swatch repeats the same pattern/shape next to the text label.\n**ARIA / content:** Series **text label** present in legend, table headers, and point `aria-label`s; pattern/shape adds a non-color visual signal. Decorative legend glyphs `aria-hidden`. \u2014 WCAG **1.4.1 Use of Color**; 1.1.1.\n**Keyboard:** N/A.\n**Tests (color/contrast):** In grayscale and forced-colors, all 3\u20135 series remain distinguishable by pattern/shape/label; text contrast \u22654.5:1; axis/mark/focus contrast \u22653:1; existing series colors measured and any failures flagged (not changed).\n**WCAG:** 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.11.\n\n### Task 7: Reduced-motion gating + final reflow/zoom pass\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint 7**\n\n**Files:** `Chart.module.css`, `Chart.tsx`.\n**Structure Stub:** Wrap entrance/transition animation in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)`; verify `rem`-based text; verify 320px + 200% behavior.\n**ARIA:** N/A (visual/motion).\n**Tests:** With `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`, animations are off/reduced; at 200% zoom labels scale and nothing clips; at 320px no horizontal page scroll.\n**WCAG:** 2.3.3, 1.4.4, 1.4.10.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus |\n|-----------|-----------|-------|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Task 1 | `role=\"img\"` + label/description resolve; summary is **data-oriented**, not a visual description; title is a real heading. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Task 2 | Table semantics correct (`scope` headers, caption, no `role=presentation`); month = `th[scope=row]`; values match source; present-but-hidden in DOM. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Task 3 | Disclosure `aria-expanded`/`aria-controls` correct; focus stays on button; **320px shows table with no horizontal scroll** (1.4.10). |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Task 4 | Roving tabindex (exactly one `0`); Arrow model correct; **no keyboard trap**; single live region; focus ring visible against all colors. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 5 | Task 5 | Tooltip **appears on focus** (1.4.13), dismissible with Esc, does not steal focus, hoverable. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 6 | Task 6 | Series distinguishable **without color** in grayscale/forced-colors (1.4.1); contrast ratios met; existing colors measured/flagged not changed. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 7 | Task 7 | Reduced-motion honored; 200% zoom and 320px reflow verified end-to-end. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d Final | All | Cross-SR (NVDA/JAWS/VoiceOver): the **data table delivers 100% of values** in every SR; axe-core 0 serious/critical across all state variants; DOM verification of all aria-* placement and reference resolution. |\n\n---\n\n### Contract Appendix (for spec-kitty-bridge WP translation)\n\n### Architecture Overview\nLayered, table-as-source-of-truth accessibility for a custom-SVG chart: (1) a labeled `role=\"figure\"` wrapper with a data-oriented `role=\"img\"` summary on the SVG; (2) a real, always-in-DOM HTML `<table>` (visually hidden, toggleable) as the guaranteed screen-reader and 320px-reflow data path; (3) a keyboard layer over the SVG data points (roving tabindex, Grid-style Arrow navigation) with the existing tooltip upgraded to appear on focus. One data source feeds all three layers so they cannot drift. Color is supplemented by pattern/shape/text so series survive grayscale and forced-colors. Visual chart, colors, tooltip visuals, and animation are unchanged (animation gated behind reduced-motion). No chart-library migration; data pipeline out of scope.\n\n### Implementation Tasks\n\n#### Task 1: Labeled figure wrapper + data-oriented SVG summary\nEstimated Effort: low\nDepends on: none\n\n#### Task 2: Visually-hidden data table (primary SR data path)\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: none (consumes the same series data the SVG already has)\n\n#### Task 3: \"Show data table\" disclosure + 320px reflow swap\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: Task 2\n\n#### Task 4: Keyboard navigation of data points (roving tabindex, Grid model)\nEstimated Effort: high\nDepends on: Task 1\n\n#### Task 5: Focus-triggered tooltip (fix 1.4.13)\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: Task 4\n\n#### Task 6: Color-independent series differentiation (legend + marks)\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: none\n\n#### Task 7: Reduced-motion gating + final reflow/zoom pass\nEstimated Effort: low\nDepends on: Task 3, Task 6\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 1\nDOM-verify SVG `role=\"img\"` + `aria-labelledby`/`aria-describedby` resolve; assert summary text contains series names + extremes and excludes color words; assert title is a heading. WCAG 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 2.4.6, 4.1.2.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 2\nAssert 12 rows \u00d7 N series; every month cell is `th[scope=row]`, every series header `th[scope=col]`; values equal the data source; table in DOM while `.sr-only`; no `role=\"presentation\"`. WCAG 1.1.1, 1.3.1.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 3\nToggle flips `aria-expanded` and visibility, focus stays on button, `role=\"status\"` announces; `aria-controls` resolves; 320px container shows table with no horizontal page scroll (Playwright viewport test + screenshot). WCAG 1.3.1, 1.4.10, 4.1.2, 4.1.3.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 4\nReal key events: Arrows move across months/series, Home/End within series, exactly one `tabindex=0`, Tab exits both ways (no trap), single live region echoes focused value. WCAG 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 4.1.2, 4.1.3.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 5\nKeyboard-only: focusing a data point shows the tooltip with matching value; Esc hides without moving focus; tooltip never receives focus; tooltip hoverable. WCAG 1.4.13, 4.1.2.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 6\nGrayscale + forced-colors screenshots: 3\u20135 series distinguishable by pattern/shape/label; text \u22654.5:1, axis/mark/focus \u22653:1; existing colors measured and failures flagged (not changed). WCAG 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.11.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 7\n`prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` disables/reduces animation; 200% zoom scales labels with no clipping; 320px no horizontal scroll. WCAG 2.3.3, 1.4.4, 1.4.10.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 1\nSVG exposes a resolvable accessible name + a data-oriented description; title in heading list; no color-only description.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 2\nEvery one of the 36\u201360 values is reachable via a correctly-headed table in NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 3\nDisclosure state correct and announced; at 320px full data is available with no horizontal page scroll; focus unmoved on toggle.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 4\nChart is a single Tab stop with full 2-D Arrow navigation, visible focus ring on every point against every series color, no keyboard trap, one live region.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 5\nTooltip appears on keyboard focus (not hover-only), is dismissible with Escape, is hoverable, and never steals focus \u2014 WCAG 1.4.13 satisfied.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 6\nAll series distinguishable without relying on hue (grayscale + forced-colors); contrast minimums met; existing colors unchanged with any failures flagged.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 7\nReduced-motion honored; 200% zoom and 320px reflow verified with no clipping and no horizontal page scroll.\n\n### Failure Modes\n- **Summary describes appearance, not data** (\"blue and red lines\") \u2192 screen-reader users get no values. Mitigation: Task 1 test asserts data content / excludes color words.\n- **Table omitted or `display:none`** \u2192 removed from a11y tree; SR users get nothing. Mitigation: `.sr-only` clip technique + DOM-presence test.\n- **Live region placed inside the per-point loop** \u2192 dozens of competing regions, garbled/duplicate announcements. Mitigation: exactly one `role=\"status\"`, asserted singular in DOM.\n- **Tooltip stays hover-only** \u2192 1.4.13 failure for keyboard/low-vision users. Mitigation: focus-trigger test with no mouse.\n- **Series distinguishable by color only** \u2192 1.4.1 failure in grayscale/forced-colors/color-blind. Mitigation: pattern/shape + table + grayscale screenshot test.\n- **No 320px plan** \u2192 horizontal page scroll, 1.4.10 failure. Mitigation: table-swap at narrow width + viewport test.\n- **Keyboard trap** in the chart (Tab can't leave) \u2192 2.1.2 failure. Mitigation: explicit Tab-exit test both directions.\n- **`role=\"presentation\"` or `<td>` month cells** in the table \u2192 lost semantics / values announced without context. Mitigation: `th[scope=row]` assertion; no presentation role.\n- **Decorative SVG (gridlines/hover layer) left in a11y tree or focus order** \u2192 noise / stray Tab stops. Mitigation: `aria-hidden` + no `tabindex` on decorative parts, verified.\n- **Focus ring invisible against a series color or dark background** \u2192 2.4.7 failure. Mitigation: two-color double-ring, tested against every series color and both backgrounds.\n",
